5. Methodology and Evaluation Plan

5.1 Datasets

A large‑scale dataset will be constructed from PyPI, covering the period 2020–2026. The dataset includes:

· Benign packages: 500,000 packages with high download counts (top 10% by download count). These are assumed benign, though some may contain undetected malware.
· Known malicious packages: 5,000 packages from public malware databases (Backstabbers, PyPI malware feed, and the LiteLLM incident ground truth).
· Contrived malicious packages: To evaluate detection of novel attacks, 10,000 benign packages will be transformed by injecting epistemic contradictions. For each benign package, three variants are created:
  1. Data exfiltration: Add code to send local files to a remote server.
  2. Persistence: Add code to modify system cron jobs.
  3. Lateral movement: Add code to scan the local network and attempt SSH connections.
     These variants preserve the original claimed intent but introduce contradictory behavior.

5.2 Evaluation Metrics

The following metrics will be used:

· True positive rate (TPR) at a fixed false positive rate (FPR) of 1%. This is standard in security evaluation.
· Area under the ROC curve (AUC).
· Time‑to‑detection: number of runtime events observed before the system flags the package.
· Explainability: SHAP values will be used to attribute the inconsistency score to specific events.

5.3 Baselines

To demonstrate the superiority of the epistemic approach, BE‑AI will be compared against three classes of state‑of‑the‑art systems:

Class Representative Tool
Static‑only LLM PyGuard
Static heuristic GuardDog
Dynamic‑only Sandbox with YARA signatures
Hybrid (if available) Emerging tools combining static + dynamic

5.4 Ablation Study

To demonstrate the contribution of each component, an ablation study will be performed:

· BE‑AI without intent: Use only anomaly score A and provenance.
· BE‑AI without provenance: Use only \mathcal{I} without provenance weighting.
· BE‑AI without LLM: Replace intent extraction with a rule‑based system (e.g., using README keywords).
· BE‑AI without Wasserstein: Use only KL divergence.
· BE‑AI with only KL: Compare against full combination.

5.5 Statistical Significance

All performance comparisons will be accompanied by 95% confidence intervals computed via bootstrap resampling. Statistical significance (e.g., McNemar’s test) will be reported to ensure that observed improvements are not due to chance.

5.6 Implementation Details

BE‑AI will be implemented in Python 3.10. The LLM will be a fine‑tuned CodeLlama‑7B, quantized to 4‑bit for inference. The VGAE will be implemented in PyTorch Geometric, with a 3‑layer GIN encoder and a 2‑layer MLP decoder. Sandboxing will use Docker with eBPF via the bpftrace tool. The system will run on a single node with 128 GB RAM and one NVIDIA A100 GPU.

5.7 Limitations

Sandbox evasion, LLM hallucination in intent extraction, and computational cost of full behavioral tracing on every package remain challenges. These will be mitigated via static pre‑filtering (only sandbox packages with suspicious static signals), a two‑stage intent pipeline, and selective deep sandboxing. Future adversarial robustness studies will address manipulation of documentation or behavioral graphs. Additionally, class imbalance in real‑world data (malicious packages are rare) may affect performance; this will be addressed with resampling and cost‑sensitive learning.

5.8 Real‑World Deployment Simulation

To evaluate practical applicability, BE‑AI will be integrated into a simulated CI/CD pipeline where packages are analyzed pre‑installation. Detection latency, computational overhead, and developer impact (false positive burden) will be measured.

5.9 Generalization Test

To evaluate zero‑day detection capability, the model will be trained on packages up to year Y, and tested on packages from year Y+1, ensuring temporal separation and preventing data leakage. This will measure the framework’s ability to detect novel attacks not seen during training.

