8. Conclusion

Software supply chain attacks represent a fundamental breakdown of trust in digital ecosystems. Traditional defenses fail because they treat security as a pattern‑matching problem rather than a reasoning problem. This thesis demonstrates that by reframing security as epistemic consistency, systems can be built that not only detect attacks but also explain why they are malicious.

This work is the first to treat software behavior as an epistemic object whose validity is determined by internal consistency across multiple representations. BE‑AI, a unified framework integrating LLMs, graph neural networks, and provenance verification under a Bayesian trust model, has been presented. The theoretical analysis shows asymptotic convergence to ground truth, and the evaluation plan promises state‑of‑the‑art detection rates with explainability.

This work suggests that software security is fundamentally a problem of computational epistemology: determining whether a system’s behavior can be coherently explained under its claimed model of operation. In this view, malicious software is not merely anomalous—it is epistemically inconsistent. This distinction enables detection strategies that are invariant to implementation details, obfuscation, and attack novelty.

This work lays the foundation for a new generation of security systems that reason about software behavior with human‑like understanding, enabling autonomous ecosystems that can be trusted by design.

