Appendix A: Formal Proof of Asymptotic Trust Convergence

Theorem 1 (Asymptotic Epistemic Trust Convergence).
Let Y \in \{0,1\} be the true state (1 = benign, 0 = malicious). Let E_1, E_2, \dots be conditionally independent and identically distributed evidence vectors, each drawn from f(E \mid Y). Define the posterior trust score after n observations as

T_n = P(Y=1 \mid E_1,\dots,E_n) = \frac{\pi_1 \prod_{i=1}^n f(E_i \mid Y=1)}{\pi_1 \prod_{i=1}^n f(E_i \mid Y=1) + \pi_0 \prod_{i=1}^n f(E_i \mid Y=0)},

where \pi_1 = P(Y=1) and \pi_0 = P(Y=0) are prior probabilities. Then

\lim_{n\to\infty} T_n = \mathbb{1}\{Y=1\} \quad \text{almost surely}.

Proof. Consider the likelihood ratio

L_n = \frac{\prod_{i=1}^n f(E_i \mid Y=0)}{\prod_{i=1}^n f(E_i \mid Y=1)}.

If Y=1, then the factors f(E_i \mid Y=0)/f(E_i \mid Y=1) are i.i.d. with mean

\mathbb{E}\left[\frac{f(E \mid Y=0)}{f(E \mid Y=1)} \,\middle|\, Y=1\right] = \int \frac{f(e \mid Y=0)}{f(e \mid Y=1)} f(e \mid Y=1) \, de = \int f(e \mid Y=0) \, de = 1.

Hence L_n is a non‑negative martingale with respect to the filtration \mathcal{F}_n = \sigma(E_1,\dots,E_n). By the Martingale Convergence Theorem, L_n converges almost surely to a finite limit L_\infty.

If the distributions f(\cdot \mid Y=0) and f(\cdot \mid Y=1) are distinct, Kullback’s theorem states that L_n \to 0 almost surely when Y=1, and L_n \to \infty almost surely when Y=0. A standard reference is the Kullback–Leibler divergence:

D_{\text{KL}}(f(\cdot \mid Y=1) \| f(\cdot \mid Y=0)) > 0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad L_n \to 0 \ \text{a.s. under } Y=1,
\]  

and symmetrically for the other case.

Now the posterior trust can be expressed as

T_n = \frac{\pi_1}{\pi_1 + \pi_0 L_n}.

Thus

\lim_{n\to\infty} T_n = 
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if } Y=1 \ (\text{since } L_n \to 0),\\
0 & \text{if } Y=0 \ (\text{since } L_n \to \infty).
\end{cases}

∎

Corollary 1 (Exponential Rate). Under the same assumptions, the probability of error decays exponentially fast. Let

C = -\min_{0\le \lambda \le 1} \log \int f(e \mid Y=1)^{\lambda} f(e \mid Y=0)^{1-\lambda} \, de > 0

be the Chernoff information. Then for any \epsilon > 0,

P(T_n \le 1-\epsilon \mid Y=1) = O(e^{-nC}), \quad
P(T_n \ge \epsilon \mid Y=0) = O(e^{-nC}).

