Appendix D: Wasserstein Distance and Its Role

D.1 Definition

For two probability distributions \mu, \nu on a metric space (\mathcal{X}, d), the 1‑Wasserstein distance is

W_1(\mu,\nu) = \inf_{\gamma \in \Gamma(\mu,\nu)} \int_{\mathcal{X}\times\mathcal{X}} d(x,y) \, d\gamma(x,y),

where \Gamma(\mu,\nu) is the set of couplings with marginals \mu and \nu. In our discrete setting, it can be computed via linear programming.

D.2 Why Complement KL?

KL divergence is sensitive to pointwise probability mass but does not capture geometric proximity. An adversary who gradually shifts behavior (e.g., from writing to /var/log to writing to /tmp and then to /root/.ssh) will incur a small KL change if the probability mass shifts across similar events. Wasserstein distance directly measures the cost of moving mass, making it suitable for detecting slow distributional shifts.

D.3 Combination

We define the total inconsistency as

\mathcal{I} = \lambda_{\text{KL}} \cdot D_{\text{KL}}(q_B \| \tilde{p}_C) + \lambda_{W_1} \cdot W_1(q_B, \tilde{p}_C) + \lambda_{\text{latent}} \cdot D_{\text{KL}}(z \| \mathcal{N}(0,I)).

The weights \lambda are tuned on a validation set to balance detection and false positives.

