Appendix E: Variational Graph Autoencoder Formulation

E.1 Model Structure

Let G = (V, E) be a behavioral graph with adjacency matrix A \in \{0,1\}^{N\times N} and node features X \in \mathbb{R}^{N \times d}. The VGAE consists of:

· Encoder: a Graph Isomorphism Network (GIN) that computes node embeddings H = \text{GIN}(X, A). Then two separate MLPs produce mean \mu and log‑variance \log \sigma^2 for each node, aggregated to a global latent vector z \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu, \sigma^2 I).
· Decoder: a bilinear form p(A_{ij} = 1 \mid z) = \sigma(z_i^\top z_j), where z_i are node‑wise latent embeddings (obtained by repeating z or by per‑node MLP from z).

E.2 Loss Function

The VGAE is trained on benign graphs to minimize

\mathcal{L} = \underbrace{-\sum_{(i,j) \in E} \log \sigma(z_i^\top z_j) - \sum_{(i,j) \notin E} \log(1 - \sigma(z_i^\top z_j))}_{\text{reconstruction loss}} + \beta \cdot D_{\text{KL}}( \mathcal{N}(\mu, \sigma^2) \| \mathcal{N}(0,I) ).

The first term is the binary cross‑entropy for graph reconstruction. The second term regularizes the latent distribution to a standard Gaussian.

E.3 Anomaly Score

For a test graph G_{\text{test}}, we encode it to obtain \mu_{\text{test}}, \sigma_{\text{test}}^2 and then compute

A_{\text{latent}} = D_{\text{KL}}( \mathcal{N}(\mu_{\text{test}}, \sigma_{\text{test}}^2) \| \mathcal{N}(0,I) ),

A_{\text{recon}} = \text{reconstruction error (binary cross‑entropy)}.

The final anomaly score is A = \alpha A_{\text{latent}} + \beta A_{\text{recon}}. This is incorporated into the epistemic inconsistency via \lambda_{\text{latent}}.

