Appendix F: Datasets and Preprocessing Details

F.1 PyPI Data Collection

We will download all packages from PyPI that were uploaded between January 1, 2020, and December 31, 2025, using the pypi-simple API. For each package, we store:

· Package name, version, and upload timestamp.
· Source distribution (.tar.gz) and/or wheel (.whl).
· Metadata: description, author, license, dependencies.

F.2 Ground Truth Malware Labels

We will combine labels from:

· Backstabbers (public dataset of PyPI malware, 2020–2024).
· PyPI Malware Feed (maintained by security researchers, updated daily).
· LiteLLM incident (March 2026, ground truth from post‑mortem analysis).

Manual verification will be performed for a subset to ensure quality.

F.3 Benign Package Selection

We will select the top 500,000 packages by download count (as of January 2026) that are not present in any malware database. We assume these are benign, acknowledging that some may contain undiscovered malware (label noise). We will later filter using an ensemble of existing scanners to reduce noise.

F.4 Contrived Malicious Variants

For 10,000 randomly selected benign packages, we will generate three variants each:

· Data exfiltration: Insert code that periodically reads /etc/passwd and sends it to a remote IP via HTTPS, after a delay of 30 seconds.
· Persistence: Insert code that adds a cron job or systemd service that launches a backdoor.
· Lateral movement: Insert code that scans the local network for open SSH ports and attempts to log in with stolen credentials.

All variants keep the original documentation unchanged, preserving the claimed intent.

